<h3 id="hybrid-organising-systems-are-often-best">Hybrid organising systems are often&nbsp;best</h3>
<p>My plain text notes are organised in a hybrid fashion, with granular, static folders for things that donâ€™t change (the <a href="https://johnnydecimal.com/10-19-concepts/14-build-your-system/14.11-life-admin/" target="_blank">Johnny Decimal Life Admin system</a>) and one big folder called <span class="small-caps">ALL</span> <span class="small-caps">THE</span> <span class="small-caps">NOTES</span> for everything else.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>tags are essentially a way of organizing your files into folders without having to do any of the dragging and dropping yourself â€” Trystan</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And index pages are fabulous thinking-spaces for bringing notes together into structured thought progressions. Itâ€™s wise to tag each index page as such. (See <a href="https://forum.zettelkasten.de/discussion/2755/how-do-you-find-the-proper-index-note" target="_blank">this discussion</a> on the Zettelkasten.de forum)</p>
